<h2>The Question</h2>

<p>Web Validation's generation layer (<a href="/backlog/085-validation-adapters-multi-language/">#085</a>) shipped a v1 <strong>shape-only</strong> intent vocabulary — 13 closed intents (<code>required</code>, <code>type</code>, <code>min</code>/<code>max</code>, <code>pattern</code>, <code>format</code>, <code>min-items</code>/<code>max-items</code>, <code>enum</code>, <code>custom</code>) that each emit statically to every <strong>Mode-1</strong> target (HTML, Zod, Pydantic, JSON Schema). What it deliberately deferred is <strong>cross-field and conditional logic</strong> — <em>"endDate after startDate"</em>, <em>"require X when Y = z"</em> — because that's exactly where the Mode-1 fidelities diverge: protovalidate carries a portable rule language (CEL), JSON-Schema codegen is shape-only, Standard Schema is interface-only. The fork (<a href="/backlog/465-portable-cross-field-rule-expression-language-or-stay-shape-/">#465</a>): <strong>define/adopt a portable rule-expression layer so cross-field emits to all Mode-1 targets, or stay shape-only and treat cross-field as Mode-2-only</strong> (the server evaluates it). This decides whether every <code>CustomValidationAdapter</code> must carry an expression compiler.</p>

<h2>What we found</h2>

<p><strong>The decision is not the binary it first looks like.</strong> Mode-2 (server-authoritative validation-as-a-service) already gives cross-field a fully-settled home — the 2026-06-06 report fixed its wire format at RFC 9457 <code>application/problem+json</code> via Laravel-Precognition-style "run the real rules, skip the controller." So cross-field <em>works today</em> regardless of this fork. The real question is narrower: <strong>does WE additionally invest in <em>portable Mode-1</em> cross-field (static emission to every target language with no network), and if so, in what representation?</strong></p>

<h2>The portable-rule-language landscape</h2>

