<h2>How this lands on the architecture</h2>

<p>Today's <code>CustomValidationAdapter</code> (<code>validation-generation/provider.ts:135-147</code>) carries a declared-compliance <code>intents[]</code> surface (<code>:144</code>) and an <code>emit()</code> that materializes a declaration into a target format (<code>:146</code>). The vocabulary is shape-only, and the <em>only</em> predicate escape hatch is the <strong>non-portable</strong> <code>custom</code> intent (<code>:57</code>) — a target-specific function, not something that emits to five languages. Adopting a portable rule layer means <code>emit()</code> must additionally translate a <em>neutral rule expression</em> into each target's idiom (CEL string + embedded runtime, or transpile to Zod <code>.refine()</code> / Pydantic <code>model_validator</code> / etc.).</p>

<p>Crucially, the <strong>graceful-degradation seam already exists</strong>: <code>cross-field</code> and <code>conditional</code> are declared as <em>optional capability features</em> in the manifest (<code>capability-manifest/provider.ts:48-50</code>), under the standing rule "absence is reportable, never a silent no-op." So an adapter can already declare it does <em>not</em> support cross-field, and the manifest flags those rules lossy — they fall back to Mode-2 rather than vanishing. That <code>$vocabulary</code>-style required/optional model (grounded in the 2026-06-06 report) means <strong>portable cross-field can be a per-adapter capability, not an all-or-nothing contract requirement</strong>.</p>

<h2>Recommendation carried into #465</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Keep the v1 adapter contract shape-only-required.</strong> Don't force every adapter (the slices #305–#309) to carry an expression compiler. Most flexible default: cross-field is an <em>opt-in</em> adapter capability, not a baseline requirement.</li>
  <li><strong>Mode-2 is the default authoritative home for cross-field now</strong> — already settled (RFC 9457 + precognition). Cross-field is never "missing"; it's server-evaluated unless an adapter opts into Mode-1 emission.</li>
  <li><strong>A portable Mode-1 cross-field layer is a deferred opt-in — and IF/when built, it adopts CEL</strong>, not a minted WE format, not JSONLogic, not JSON-Schema-conditionals-only. CEL is the proven multi-language interop language; reusing it is the native-first / borrow-official-vocabulary move (same discipline as <code>Intl.Collator</code> / <code>aria-sort</code>).</li>
  <li><strong>Transpile-to-native vs embed-a-runtime is an adapter implementation detail</strong>, not a standards fork — the contract stays representation-neutral about how an adapter realizes a rule.</li>
</ul>

